<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF208-106-902  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 106 902.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronics  April 1989 v62 n4 p32(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>A new look for fiber: plastic replaces glass. (fiber-opticEthernet gets more affordable)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Shandle, Jack.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Three developments in fiber optic technology are expected toenable fiber-optic Ethernet local-area networks (LANs) to competeon a cost-per-node basis with standard unshielded twisted-pairtelephone wiring.andP;  The first is Codenoll Technology Corp's(Yonkers, NY) development of light-emitting diodes sufficientlypowerful to drive passive Ethernet optical hubs and eliminate theneed for electronic components in the hub.andP;  The use of plasticfiber to replace glass fibers is also reducing the cost of fiberoptic LANs.andP;  The final development is the expected Nov 1989release of a fiber-optic Ethernet LAN standard by the 10BaseTcommittee of the IEEE.andP;  The committee is developing bothactive-star and passive-star topologies; their relative merits arebriefly discussed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Codenoll Technology Corp. (innovations).andO;Topic:     Optical communicationsFiber OpticsEthernetLocal Area NetworksTechnologyNew TechniqueCablesCost of Communications.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Mixing rod-star coupler. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>